value.0: This thick, dark, almost black wine, made in the Old Empires, is named for the fire it creates in one's belly.  Fire wine is an extremely strong and spicy wine, reputed to have medicinal qualities.

Southern brews, including these Calishite brews, are rare and lihgter drinks known as lager.  They are lighter not only in taste, but in color and weight, and have mosre effervescence.  Golden sands brews come in varying types, each with different additives to alter the taste of the base beverage: basic, gold and orange.
Passing fare for tavern or home consumption, this dark amber liquid has a harsh, bitter aftertaste (revered by Iriaeborans as "the bite of the north wind") that is, for many, an acquired taste.
This good wine is often bought in bulk as provisioning for a tavern, castle, or manor.  It supplies a merry evening and is unfailingly tasty.
A pale chartreuse wine renowned for its faint luminescence, glowfire is neither sweet nor very dry, and has a taste reminiscent of pears.

Typically from Calimshan and Tethyr, spiced wine is a taste treat and a sovereign remedy for many ailments, including nausea, cough, and huskiness of the throat.  Raisin, cinnamon, fennel, anise, nutmeg and clove varieties are available.
This unmarked and undistinguished red wine is sourced from some third-rate Moonshaes vinyard and tastes like it.
This bowl contains a hot broth mixed with pieces of meat and assorted vegetables.
Produced from cow's milk, cheese is a delicious food that goes well with a good wine.
Fish helps make a healthy meal for those who can't afford meat.
Bread is the staple food of the commoner, both filling and nutritious.
This run-of-the-mill meal isn't the finest fare in Faern, but nourishing and filling nonetheless.
